Learning objectives

  • Describe the anatomical structure of skeletal muscle cells and their components.
  • Describe the mechanisms of skeletal muscle contraction/relaxation and how these mechanisms relate tothe force produced.
  • Explain how the Nerve-Muscle relationship relates to the properties of muscle contractions.
  • Explain how a muscle cell meets its energy demands and how the energy demands relate to function.
  • Suggested reading
    • Chapter 11 of Saladin, Anatomy & Physiology: The Unity of Form and Function 9e
      • 11.1, 11.2, 11.3, 11.4, 11.5 and 11.6

Muscle tissue

  • Muscle tissue characteristics
    • Excitability
      • They respond to stimuli with changes in membrane potential
      • They are conductive because local excitation initiates a wave of excitation that travels along the cell
    • Contractility
      • They can shorten when stimulated
      • They display extensibility by stretching again between contractions
    • Elasticity
      • When a muscle cell is stretched and released, it recoils to a shorter length

Types of muscle

  • Skeletal muscle
    • Attaches to and covers the skeleton
    • Voluntary contractions for overall body motility
    • Striated appearance withsingle long/cylindrical multinucleate cells
  • Cardiac muscle
    • Only exists in the heart
    • Involuntary (contracts without direct stimulation from the nervous system)
    • Striated appearance with branching chains oruni(bi)nucleated cells
  • Smooth muscle
    • Present in the walls of hollow organs
    • Involuntary (autonomic nervous system stimulation)
    • No striations with single fusiformuninucleatedcells

Anatomy of the muscle

  • Muscle cells are very long and often called muscle fibers ormyofibres
  • Muscles are not just muscle tissue, but also connective tissue
    • For example
      • Endomysium around each musclefibre
      • Perimysium around bundles muscle fibers to create fascicles
      • Epimysium around the entire muscle
    • These connective tissues are continuouswith the collagenfibresof tendons (and bones)
    • Collagen is not excitable, but isextensible and elastic

Myofilaments

  • Thick filaments
    • Comprises of 100s of myosin proteins
      • Myosin is shaped like a golf ball (two chains are intertwined toform a tail and double globular head)
  • Thin filaments
    • Comprises of ~2 actin proteins
      • Actin is shaped like a bead necklace (a string of globular actinsubunits that have an active site that can bind to the myosinhead)
    • Also comprises of tropomyosin (which blocks multiple activesites on the actin in the resting state)
      • Tropomyosin has a smaller protein, called troponin, that canbind to calcium

    • A springy protein called titin thatruns through the middle of thickfilaments
    • Connects The Z disc and M line

Figure 11.5

Skeletal Muscle Contraction

  • Skeletal muscle is under voluntary control, so the contractions are initiated by action potentials in thenervous system
  • A skeletal muscle contraction involves the following steps
    • Action potential in neuron is transmitted to muscle fibre atneuromuscular junction
    • Action potential in the muscle initiatesexcitation-contraction coupling
    • Contraction of the muscle occurs viasliding filament theory
    • Muscle fibre relaxes and returns to resting state, called therelaxation phase

Neuromuscular junction

  • The neuromuscular junction is a synapse between aneuron and a muscle fibre
    • A form of chemical communication whereby an actionpotential in the axon results in an action potential inthe muscle fibre
  • Steps
    • Action potential depolarises axon terminal
    • Depolarisation activates voltage-gate Ca2+channels
    • Ca2+causes exocytosis of vesicles, releasingACh
    • AChdiffuses across the synapse and binds to receptorchannels on the motor end plate
    • Channels open to cause a depolarisation (end platepotential) and this current opens voltage-gated Na+channels in the adjacent membrane, starting an actionpotential in the muscle fibre
    • AChis metabolised by acetylcholinesterase

Excitation-contraction coupling

  • Action potential in the muscle fibre propagates down the t-tubules

Figure 11.9

Excitation-contraction coupling

  • Action potential in the t-tubule alters the conformation of the DHP (dihydropyridine) receptor
  • DHP receptor open ryanodine release (RyR) channel on the terminal cistern of the sarcoplasmic reticulum
  • RyRreleases Ca2+into cytoplasm which binds to troponin
  • The shifting of tropomyosin exposes the active sites on actin

Silverthorn, Human Physiology

Figure 12.10

Contractionsliding filament theory

  • The contraction is where the muscle fibre develops tension andmay shorten
  • Steps
    • Myosin uses ATP to activate the head (moves to high energyposition)
    • A cross-bridge between myosin and actin is formed
    • The power stroke, where the myosin flexes into a bend (lowenergy position) pulling the thin filament along with it
    • The binding of a new ATP to myosin destabilizes the myosin-actin bond and breaks the cross-bridge
    • The myosin head undergoes a recovery stroke, hydrolysing theATP to activate the head (first step)

Figure 11.10

Relaxation phase

  • When a nerve fibre stops stimulating a muscle fibre, the muscle fibre relaxes and return to its restingstate

Motor Neurons and Motor Units

  • Somatic motor neurons innervate skeletal muscle cells
    • Cell bodies are located in the brainstem and spinal cord
    • Each neuron innervates multiple muscle fibres
      • Each muscle fibre is innervated by only one neuron
  • A motor unit is one neuron and all the muscle fibres it innervates
    • Behave as a single functional unit
    • The muscle fibres of a motor unit are positioned throughoutthe muscle
    • Small motor units
      • Produce fine motor control
      • Innervated by small neurons
    • Large motor units
      • Produce more strength in the contraction
      • Innervated by large neurons

Figure 11.6

Strength of muscle contraction

  • The more motor units involved in thecontraction, the greater the force of contraction
  • For physiological stimuli, the recruitment ofmotor units follows the size principle
    • Smaller, less powerful motor units withsmaller, slower nerve fibres are activated first
    • Larger, more powerful motor units with larger,faster nerve fibres are subsequently activated

Figure 11.14

Length-Tension relationship in skeletal muscle

  • The tension generated by a skeletal muscleduring a contraction depends on the length ofthe muscle
    • This is due to the amount of overlap betweenthe thick and thin filaments

Figure 11.12

Skeletal muscle contraction and stimulusfrequency

  • For a given stimulus intensity (voltage),the force of muscle contraction will varywith the stimulus frequency
    • Usually referred to as temporalsummation
  • A twitch is the quick cycle of contractionand relaxation for a single stimulus
  • If a second twitch is stimulated before thefirst twitch has finished the cycle, agreater force will be produced
    • Consider intracellular concentrations ofcalcium and the number of bindingsites
  • Tetanus is a sustained contraction
    • Can be incomplete or complete (fused)

What physiological mechanisms can be utilised to vary the strength of contraction in a whole skeletalmuscle?

  • The number of motor units
  • The length of muscle
  • The frequency of stimulation
  • Other factors (not physiological mechanisms) that can influence the tension produced include fatigue,temperature and hydration

Muscle Metabolism

  • All muscle contractions depend on ATP
  • The supply of ATP depends on the availability of oxygen and organic fuels (glucose and fatty acids)
  • The two main pathways for ATP synthesis
    • Anaerobic fermentation
      • Produces ATP without oxygen, but yield is limited
      • The process generates lactic acid
    • Aerobic respiration
      • Produces far more ATP and does not produce lactic acid
      • Requires a constant supply of oxygen
  • Also consider thephosphagensystem
    • Myokinaseconverts 2 ADP molecules into ATP and AMP
    • Creatinekinase converts ADP andcreatinephosphate into ATP andcreatine

Muscle Fatigue

  • High intensity short duration exercise produces fatigue via
    • Potassium accumulation
      • Each action potential releases K+from the sarcoplasm to ECF, which hyperpolarises the cell andinterferes with the release of calcium from the SR
    • ADP/Phosphate accumulation
      • ADP slows the cross-bridge cycling mechanism
      • Phosphate inhibits calcium release from the SR
  • Low intensity long duration exercise produces fatigue via
    • Fuel depletion
      • Reduced levels of glycogen in muscle and glucose in the blood
    • Electrolyte loss
      • Perspiration can alter ion balance enough in ECF to reduce muscle excitability
    • Central fatigue
      • Exercising muscles produce ammonia, which inhibits motor neurons in the cerebrum?

Fast and Slow twitch fibres

  • Slow twitch fibres
    • Also called slow oxidative or type I fibres
    • Are well adapted for endurance and fatigue resistance
      • Specialised for aerobic respiration, so they are surrounded by blood capillaries, high number ofmitochondria and a high concentration of myoglobin
    • Important in muscles that support the body and maintain posture
  • Fast twitch fibres
    • Also called fast glycolytic or type II fibres
    • Are well adapted for quick response
      • Extensive SR with fast release/reabsorption and a form of myosin with quick ATP hydrolysis andcross-bridge cycling
    • Depend primarily on anaerobic fermentation
      • High concentrations of glycogen,ceratinephosphate, fewermitochondiaand are thicker fibres(oxygen diffuse)
    • Important in eye muscles, hand muscles and large muscles required for explosive movements
